\par\par \uc2 CE Noticias Financieras English\par {\*\bkmkstart toc0}{\*\bkmkend toc0}\b \uc2 A. Latin America, democracy without democrats, by Juan De la Puente\b0\par\par\uc2 1,078 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 December 2024\par \uc2 CE NoticiasFinancieras\par \uc2 NFINCE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright \u169\'00\'A9 Content Engine LLC \par \par \uc2 In Latin America, the year that is ending had no major milestones. Not until the recent declarations of US President-elect \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  to recover the Panama Canal (actually force a renegotiation), relaunch the war on drugs with eyes on Mexico and unleash a trade war against China, Canada and Mexico.\par \par \uc2 Trump's threats are likely to revive a new form of regional anti-imperialism, although the other polarizations will prevent a traditional north/south or center/periphery cross-section. The mere prospect of these announcements - difficult to deliver in full and even in a relative way - adds further disarray to a region where, to the chagrin of analysts, the familiar pieces no longer fit together.\par \par \uc2 The fact is that there are new pieces and, in the disorder, the local pieces are more decisive than the regional trends. In fact, although most of the elections held in Latin America in 2024 met electoral standards (Panama, Dominican Republic, Mexico and Uruguay), they failed to project the general image of a healthy democracy in the region.\par \par \uc2 Elections continue to be the formula for elucidating the ownership of government, although the keys to the exercise of power are marked by high levels of uncertainty, surprise and inefficiency from which almost no administration is spared. The rapid erosion of governments is impressive and more and more of them are failing in a very short period of time.\par \par \uc2 Immediate failure is added to the phenomenon of the erosion of traditional parties, which is becoming more acute (Mexico, Panama, El Salvador and the Dominican Republic in 2024) in a region where harsh criticism of the liberal system of representation, rights and freedoms and the debacle of the so-called political center are openly combined. This complexity implies the failure of the liberal promise from within and without.\par \par \uc2 To elucidate what is from "inside" and what are the attacks "from outside" is a challenging exercise. From the ranks of the democrats, the reflection that the attacks on democracy come from non-democratic tendencies located outside the system is absolutized. However, there is evidence of a pincer process where outsiders and insiders go hand in hand through the encounter between the authoritarian/mafioso capture of the State and the activity of society -mobilized or demobilized- that changes democratic politics.\par \par \uc2 In several countries, democracy is being redefined with varying degrees of intensity, reducing it to an electoral procedure that reduces its plurality and its guarantee of renewal of the system (Ecuador and Guatemala 2023, El Salvador and Venezuela 2024 and very probably Bolivia 2025 and Peru 2026).\par \par \uc2 Even with elections that may surpass the evaluation of the minimum acceptable, in 2024 the de-democratization advanced. The data of the recent Latinobar\u243\'00\'F3metro ("Resilient Democracy") allow us to appreciate the progress of this process. It is true that there is an advance of 4 points (52%) with respect to the previous year in support for democracy, but when we run the zipper of conventional data or go deeper into perceptions with new questions, the keys to de-democratization appear.\par \par \uc2 The contradiction between the feeling of well-being, apparently with figures in blue, and the need for change is relevant. According to the study, life satisfaction reached its highest level since 1997 in 2024, so that 79% consider themselves to be very or fairly satisfied with their lives, with Costa Rica, Uruguay and Guatemala among the most satisfied; and Chile, Peru and Bolivia among the least satisfied.\par \par \uc2 However, the study indicates that only 28% of those who perceive that their country is progressing, while 25% consider that their country is "regressing" and 45% believe that their country "is stagnating".\par \par \uc2 The demand in relation to State/society, that is, more democracy, rights and freedoms, has other keys. The idea of two decades ago that the country is doing well, but not the economy and personal wellbeing, seems to have been replaced by another, that "the country is bad, but I am better off". In the intricacies of this perception lies the deep gap between society and the State and between democratic politics and other forms of anti-politics. For the same reason, it is understandable that in some territories of several countries in the region there is no demand for more State, but less State, and that the territories liberated by informal and illegal economies and organized crime are expanding.\par \par \uc2 The aforementioned gaps appear when support for democracy is contrasted with the demand for change which, according to the study, presents three thirds: 35% in favor of "small changes", 29% in favor of "deep reforms", and 26% in favor of "radical" change. A recomposition of the options would indicate that those in favor of deep and/or far-reaching change are close to 60%. This perception exceeds two thirds in Chile, Argentina, Ecuador, Bolivia and Peru.\par \par \uc2 The issue in the region is no longer the democracy-change continuum, but only change, without ensuring that this change is necessarily democratic. There is an addition: authoritarian reversals and the hollowing out of democracy can be seen, unlike in the 60s and 70s, as democratic processes, as in El Salvador, Argentina and Peru, and earlier in the ALBA countries.\par \par \uc2 The idea of democracy without democracy does not seem to be an oxymoron in several countries of the region. According to the same Latinobar\u243\'00\'F3metro, 1 in 4 Latin American citizens do not care whether a regime is democratic or not, in 10 of the 17 countries studied, more than 50% do not support democracy and in three (El Salvador, Ecuador and Paraguay), half agree that the president of the Republic should override the laws, the Congress and the institutions.\par \par \uc2 The thesis that the hollowing out of democracy is a process that is located in the elites and in the government of the institutions (the idea of the centrality of agency) should be debated. In five countries of the region (Ecuador, Colombia, Paraguay, Panama and Peru), more than half of the citizens believe that democracy can function without parties, while in countries that have led the recovery of democracy in recent decades the conviction that there is no democracy without parties is low, in Chile 50%, Brazil 46% and Guatemala 40%. In Panama this data is consistent with others: the first force in Congress is the free nomination parliamentarians, while the winning party in the elections has strong links with corruption.\par \par \uc2 Document NFINCE0020241229ekct004bq\par }\par }}